<Zhukov42DeBr> <The summer of 1942 had seen no greater front movements in the central sector of the East front. The units of Heeresgruppe Mitte were able to establish a fairly stable defensive position. But a Soviet bulge existed in the front, with the western and southernmost point being Rzhev. It was clear that the Soviets would use this position to lash out southward. The units of Luftflotte 2 had been severely weakened during the last months, major units were transferred both to Luftflotte 4 and the Mediterranean front.  The Soviets are also becoming more and more aggressive and better in tactics. Luftflotte 2 in this area only has the two Gruppen of JG 51 Mölders, the KG 4 and several staffeln of Stukas, as well as a new Hs 129 squadron, forming Gefechtsverband Schmidt. Gefechtsverband Schmidt is tasked with close support against the advancing Soviets as well as air defence.>
<Zhukov42DeDb> <The Soviets succeeded in throwing back Heeresgruppe Mitte further, but the main goal, trapping large forces of it in a huge pocket west of Vyasma has not been accomplished. The Wehrmacht managed to withdraw from the Vyasma bulge during the Büffel movement without great losses. In a movement war, losing territory is preferrable to losing troops. The scratch formation, Gefechtsverband Schmidt, was instrumental in this move, it kept constant pressure on the Soviets. The new Fw 190s have proven themselves to be very suited for East front conditions. After the setbacks of the winter, our forces are still intact and we will turn the tide this summer!>
<Zhukov42RuBr> <After the difficult battles of summer 1942, the central front before Moscow remained quiet. The Germans threw all their forces in the advance in the south, while we were gathering strength. The frontline gives us the opportunity to try a pincer operation southward from the bulge at Rzhew in an attempt to isolate and destroy most of the German forces on the Moscow front, an accompanying operation to the one being mounted at Stalingrad, though we have been delayed by bad weather. Our southern armies are far from German territory: it is in the north that the fascists must be beaten.  In order for our offensive to succeed, the VVS must wrestle air superiority from the Germans and enable our troops to operate without a threat from German bombers.>
<Zhukov42RuDb> <Our attacks south of Rzhev were not able to complete the isolation of the German occupiers and the attacks made further west did not even threaten an encirclement.  The strategic goal of our offensive was not met and the operation must be counted a failure, though it did prevent the fascists using their best troops to reinforce the weak armies of their allies in the south. The VVS has once again proven itself. Our fighters managed to master air combat against the new German fighters, while our ground attackers were more efficient than ever in supporting our troops.>
