<Leningrad44SummerRuDb> <Leningrad is free again! We have broken the siege and the Red Army is rapidly advancing in the Baltic republics. Narva has fallen and Tallinn will fall soon. The enemy forces are regrouping in the south and are forming a pocket, which we will have to eliminate in the next time. Also, our offensive in Karelia has been a huge success, we have re-established the 1940 border and the Finns have signed an honorable peace with us. Two bitter years of hunger and suffering are over for the people of Leningrad!>
<Leningrad44SummerDeDb> <The siege positions around Leningrad, shell-shocked by the massive bombardment, have been totally overrun. The new defensive line at Narva did not hold very long and it is only a matter of time until the Soviets take Tallinn. Luftflotte 1 will withdraw to Kurland to cover our forces there.>
<Leningrad44SummerFiDb> <In June, the Soviet offensive finally struck. Two Soviet armies, with over 200.000 men and thousands of tanks, supported by a huge air fleet, have attacked us. The ILV and the Germans have fought bravely, shooting down 800 planes, but were not able to keep air supremacy. With massive German help, we were able to stop the Soviet offensive just on the 1940 border, but we cannot maintain this line for long. We have to negotiate for peace or the very existence of our country will be at stake.>


<KBFBaltic41RuBr> <The Germans have broken through our defences around Riga, capturing the city within the first two weeks of the war. Now they hold Tallinn and they are pressing forward towards the borders of Mother Russia herself! Leningrad lies within their reach, with the Finns already closing on the city from the north. The Germans have momentarily slowed their advance, with their tanks waiting for the infantry and supplies to catch up. Now is the moment to throw what we have at them. Unfortunately our resources are low. The Germans destroyed almost our entire Army air force in the area at Libava and Kaunas. Now the air force of the Baltic Fleet is to be thrown into their path. Our Regiment has modern MiG-3's to combat their aircraft and older I-16 and I-153 fighters to strafe and bomb their positions. Pilot - uphold the glory of the Navy and the Red Banner of the Revolution.>
<KBFBaltic41RuDb> <We fought gloriously against the invader but our Regiment has few planes remaining and the Panzers are rolling again. We have been ordered to fall back towards Leningrad. You are to be sent ahead by train with the 3rd Eskadrilya to pick up new and better fighters at Oranienbaum.>

<GOF41WinterDeBr> <As of Nov 1, 1941 Army Group North and the Finnish I and IV Korps have almost completely surrounded Leningrad. Just to the east we are closing on Tikhvin which is a main rail center supporting Leningrad. We have been unable to penetrate the city's main defences, but have effectively blockaded it. When Moscow is taken, those troops will help in the final assault against the city./n/nWith the Ladogasee freezing, the Bolsheviks will try to supply the city over the frozen lake. We must take every step to keep the "Eisbahn" closed and to keep up pressure all along the northern front. Bf-109F4s of JG54 "Green Hearts", based at Siverskaya, will sweep the skies of enemy aircraft. The Ju-87's of the Stukageschwadern and our level bombers from KG1 and KG4 will annihilate the enemy on the ground and the Red Banner Baltic Fleet at their "safe" anchorage in Leningrad.>

<GOF41WinterRuBr> <As of Nov 1, 1941 The Germans and their Finnish allies have nearly surrounded Leningrad. The only routes open are over the frozen surface of Lake Ladoga. Sorties conducted by the VVS-KBF in the coming weeks will be largely in support of the Ice Road. We must keep these routes open and the supply trains safe. Our armies are reinforcing to push the Fascists out of Shlisselburg and open up the land route to Leningrad. Mobile naval units of the KBF are at anchor under heavy flak protection in the Neva River, but may also need our protection. Our Sturmovik units will continue to hit the enemy wherever he is. Millions of our Comrades in Lenin's City are counting on us!>

<GOF41WinterFiBr> <As of Nov 1, 1941 We have pushed the Russians nearly back to the gates of Leningrad itself. We must keep up the pressure if we are to ensure a future free of Soviet aggression. The extreme skill and spirits of our flyers has so far given us the edge in combat against the Russians. The B-239 and G.50 are competitive with anything on the enemy side. We will continue our tempo of air operations in support of our army and to cut off Leningrad from resupply across the frozen surface of Lake Ladoga.>

<GOF41WinterDeDb> <As of Feb 28, 1942 we have kept up our pressure on Leningrad but the city still stands, the stubborn Bolsheviks would rather starve than surrender. Moscow has not yet been taken so we will have to wait indefinitely for reinforcements from Army Group Center. We have had to retreat from Tikhvin but still hold Shlisselburg. With winter nearing an end, Ladogasee will thaw and Leningrad will become an island, and the Ladogasee will become a watery tomb for any ships or barges trying to cross.>

<GOF41WinterRuDb> <As of Feb 28, 1942 the Germans have failed to take Leningrad, but we are still under siege and a terrible famine has continued in the city. We must hope the supply situation gets better in the spring when new offensives can open more supply routes. We have driven the Germans out of Tikhvin and have closed on Lyuban but the Germans still hold Shlisselburg and with it the land-route to Leningrad is still closed. The VVS-KBF and PVO regiments have fought heroically in the skies over Leningrad, preventing larger German terror raids and protecting the Red Banner Baltic fleet from being annihilated from the air. While doing so, the air regiments have taken heavily losses. For the upcoming counteroffensives, the VVS-KBF and PVO of Leningrad will have to be rebuilt.>

<GOF41WinterFiDb> <As of Feb 28, 1942 the Germans so far have failed to take Leningrad, but have put the city under a devastating siege and heavy air attacks. We have accomplished all goals of our war, but while 200.000 reservists are demobilized, a state of war still exists with the Soviet Union, even if actual combat is limited to air combat and static warfare in front of Leningrad. We will hold the front and wait how the general situation of the German-Russian war develops before entering peace negotiations on our terms with the Soviets.>


