<TunisiafFrBr> <After the defeat of May-June 1940 during the Battle of France, the Armée de l'Air (French Air Force) basically split into 2 groups: the Free French, a "small troop" continuing the fight together with the British and the Soviets, and the Vichy air force, subordinated to the new French government of Vichy, cooperating with the Germans. A large part of the Vichy armed forces were stationed in North Africa. Operation Torch took place on November 8th, 1942: US and British troops landed in Morocco and Algeria. The Vichy forces fought the Allies for 3 days and then surrendered. The local French resistance fighters in Algeria contributed significantly to this swift allied victory. Soon after, the French generals based in Algiers, the capital of Algeria, decided to cooperate with the Allies and to fight against Germany and Italy. \nOn the field, you are a member of the former Vichy air force, and as a pilot during the Battle of France, you have been quite ashamed by the previous situation; you are looking forward to continue the lost fight of 1940, against the Axis forces, and to liberate France from the Nazis. \nTo that effect, you will need a new aircraft to replace your ageing French plane from 1940. Thanks mainly to American understanding and cooperation, you will be satisfied: your squadron was just reequipped with new planes made in USA. The USA agreed to accept France as a beneficiary of the Lend-Lease system. \nUSAAF Colonel Harold Willis, a veteran of Escadrille Lafayette, the legendary squadron formed in 1916 with American volunteers who gave their life for France during World War I, made an effective lobbying to make this happen. You must make our American friends happy to help us, and show them that you deserve their valuable trust! \nChurchill also wanted Great Britain to participate to this French reequipment effort, and decided to contribute as well. As a first step in March 1943, the GC II/7 Nice is rearmed with Spitfires Mk Vc and becomes the RAF squadron 326.>
<TunisiafFrDb> <Well, we had a rough ride! After you complained about the lack of action between June 1940 and November 1942, you have not been disappointed. The Germans put a lot of pressure on allied forces in Tunisia. We had tremendous difficulties to hold our positions. At a certain stage, some of us were even forced to withdraw: for instance our colleagues from the GC II/5 "Lafayette" had to evacuate their Thélepte base. However spring has come and the German offensive has lost strength. It is now time to do our job!>

<TunisiafLFrBr> <After the defeat of May-June 1940 during the Battle of France, the Armée de l'Air (French Air Force) basically split into 2 groups: the Free French, a "small troop" continuing the fight together with the British and the Soviets, and the Vichy air force, subordinated to the new French government of Vichy, cooperating with the Germans. A large part of the Vichy armed forces were stationed in North Africa. Operation Torch took place on November 8th, 1942: US and British troops landed in Morocco and Algeria. The Vichy forces fought the Allies for 3 days and then surrendered. The local French resistance fighters in Algeria contributed significantly to this swift allied victory. Soon after, the French generals based in Algiers, the capital of Algeria, decided to cooperate with the Allies and to fight against Germany and Italy. \nOn the field, you are a member of the former Vichy air force, and as a pilot during the Battle of France, you have been quite ashamed by the previous situation; you are looking forward to continue the lost fight of 1940, against the Axis forces, and to liberate France from the Nazis. \nTo that effect, you will need a new aircraft to replace your ageing French plane from 1940. Thanks mainly to American understanding and cooperation, you will be satisfied: your squadron was just reequipped with new planes made in USA. The USA agreed to accept France as a beneficiary of the Lend-Lease system. \nUSAAF Colonel Harold Willis, a veteran of Escadrille Lafayette, the legendary squadron formed in 1916 with American volunteers who gave their life for France during World War I, made an effective lobbying to make this happen. You must make our American friends happy to help us, and show them that you deserve their valuable trust!>
<TunisiafLFrDb> <Well, we had a rough ride! After you complained about the lack of action between June 1940 and November 1942, you have not been disappointed. The Germans put a lot of pressure on allied forces in Tunisia. We had tremendous difficulties to hold our positions. At a certain stage, we were even forced to withdraw, and our fighter squadron, the GC II/5 "Lafayette" had to evacuate the Thélepte base. However spring has come and the German offensive has lost strength. It is now time to do our job! We are very pleased with our P-40s: they are fast, sturdy, well armed and quite manoeuvrable. We really wish we could have had them in May 1940... And we are going to receive brand new P-40s, of an even more recent type! Actually our losses have been very high during the winter campaign, and we have very few aircraft left anyway...>

<TunisiafTFrBr> <Since the Allies arrived in Algeria and Morocco, everything has changed. Our forces now fight together with the British and Americans. Today we are active again, and it is time to repel the Italian and German invaders out of Tunisia. We must finish our job there, before moving to the next steps: the island of Pantelleria, then Sicily, Italy... and France! You are eager to go back to your homeland, so please make an effort! Despite the delays in our reequipment, the overheating engines, maintenance trouble, breakdowns, etc, we must gain in strength, and use our weapons effectively!>
<TunisiafTFrDb> <Fine! You did not disappoint your American commanders, on the contrary. Your experience since 1940 is perceived as quite valuable, particularly since many of your American comrades just come from flying schools. The Axis forces have been completely kicked out of Tunisia, and the role of French armed forces in this campaign has been essential. It is now time to go to Italy, before we move to our mother country! The American and British commanders now trust that the French are loyal to the Allies. There are many difficulties and some misunderstandings due to the fact that we are in a transition period. There are also communication issues due to the language barrier. But we are going toward the same direction, and we are determined to continue to fight together.>

